    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "Transaction propagation becomes tricky when a transaction is not valid now, but may become valid later.  Timestamp based validity has the nice property that transaction validity change is predictable, and nodes can choose to only propagate transactions that have a validity transition within a certain time frame, so I don't think this is an impossible request.  However, that aspect is likely what will need the most thought.\r\n\r\nIf instead you are talking about having time-based triggers on executions that don't have an associated transaction, things suddenly become a whole lot more complicated.  You have to address the fact that gas costs may differ between when the transaction was sent and when the transaction executes (or finishes executing).  You also need to deal with figuring out the gas cost of storing that data indefinitely (until the triggering event occurs) and you can't just let individual nodes drop that data because it is part of state.  You also will need to figure out how the concept fits into stateless Ethereum, and how that data is synced.",
