    "body": "> Transaction propagation becomes tricky when a transaction is not valid now, but may become valid later. Timestamp based validity has the nice property that transaction validity change is predictable, and nodes can choose to only propagate transactions that have a validity transition within a certain time frame, so I don't think this is an impossible request. However, that aspect is likely what will need the most thought.\r\n\r\nNo idea what you mean.\r\n\r\n> If instead you are talking about having time-based triggers on executions that don't have an associated transaction, things suddenly become a whole lot more complicated. You have to address the fact that gas costs may differ between when the transaction was sent and when the transaction executes (or finishes executing). You also need to deal with figuring out the gas cost of storing that data indefinitely (until the triggering event occurs) and you can't just let individual nodes drop that data because it is part of state. You also will need to figure out how the concept fits into stateless Ethereum, and how that data is synced.\r\n\r\nThat the gas price may differ was addressed by me above: The sender should lend a big amount of ETH to pay for gas to the network at the time of sending transaction. All Ethereum state is store indefinitely, so no need to do something special about gas here. No idea about stateless.",
